//////////////////////
#include<stdio.h>
#include<string.h>
int main()
{
        char *m[]={"jan","feb","mar"};
        char d[][10] = {"sunhgjjghn","mon","tue"};
        printf("%s\t",m[1]);
        printf("%s\t",d[1]);
}
//////////////////////////////////////
1️⃣ First declaration
char *m[] = {"jan","feb","mar"};

This means:

m is an array of pointers to char

Each element points to a string literal

Memory concept:

m[0] → "jan"
m[1] → "feb"
m[2] → "mar"

These strings are stored in read-only memory.

2️⃣ Second declaration
char d[][10] = {"sun","mon","tue"};

This means:

d is a 2D character array

Each row can store 10 characters

Memory layout:

d[0] = "sun"
d[1] = "mon"
d[2] = "tue"

Actual storage:

d
+----------+
| s u n \0 |
| m o n \0 |
| t u e \0 |
+----------+
(each row has space for 10 chars)
3️⃣ First printf
printf("%s\t",m[1]);

m[1] → "feb"

So it prints:

feb
4️⃣ Second printf
printf("%s\t",d[1]);

d[1] → "mon"

So it prints:

mon
5️⃣ Final Output
feb    mon

(\t adds a tab space)

6️⃣ Important difference between the two declarations
Feature	                           char *m[]	                         char d[][10]
Type	                             Array of pointers	                 2D character array
Memory for strings	               Stored separately (read-only)	     Stored inside the array
Can modify characters	             ❌ Not safe	                       ✅ Safe
Example element	                    m[1] → pointer	                   d[1] → char array

7️⃣ Interview Tip

These two look similar but behave differently:

char *m[] = {"jan","feb","mar"}   // array of pointers
char d[][10] = {"sun","mon","tue"} // array of arrays
